  "prompt": "How much refund will I get on my PRS counter ticket if my seat is waitlisted even after the departure of the train? Can I board the train using it",
  "response": "If your train ticket purchased from a PRS (Passenger Reservation System) counter remains waitlisted even after the train's departure, here's what you need to know regarding refunds and boarding:\n\n### **Refund for Waitlisted Tickets After Train Departure**\n\n1. **Eligibility for Refund:**\n   - If your waitlisted ticket **does not get confirmed** by the time the train departs, you are generally eligible for a full refund of the ticket fare, **minus any applicable cancellation charges**.\n\n2. **Cancellation Charges:**\n   - The cancellation charges may vary based on how long before the departure you initiate the cancellation. Typically, the closer you are to the departure time, the higher the cancellation fee might be.\n   - For waitlisted tickets that **never get confirmed**, the refund process is straightforward, and minimal fees (if any) might be deducted.\n\n3. **How to Apply for Refund:**\n   - **Online Booking:** If you booked your ticket online (e.g., via IRCTC), you can request a refund through the website or app.\n   - **PRS Counter:** Since you mentioned purchasing from a PRS counter, you can visit the same counter or contact the railway's customer service to initiate the refund process. Ensure you have your ticket and identification proof handy.\n\n4. **Processing Time:**\n   - Refunds can take anywhere from a few days to a couple of weeks to process, depending on the payment method and the railway's refund procedures.\n\n### **Boarding the Train with a Waitlisted Ticket**\n\n1. **Waitlisted Status:**\n   - A waitlisted ticket means that your seat/berth is not confirmed at the time of booking. It depends on actual bookings and cancellations whether your ticket gets confirmed before the train departs.\n\n2. **After Train Departure:**\n   - If your ticket **remains waitlisted** even after the train has departed, **you are not permitted to board** the train using that ticket. Boarding is typically allowed only if your ticket is confirmed or holds a RAC (Reservation Against Cancellation) status, which still guarantees a seat or berth.\n\n3. **Possible Exceptions:**\n   - In rare cases, if there are last-minute cancellations or if seats become available due to passenger no-shows, waitlisted passengers might get a chance to board. However, this is not guaranteed and is dependent on the situation at the station.\n\n4. **Recommendation:**\n   - Always check the status of your ticket **before** the scheduled departure time. If it remains waitlisted and you need to travel, consider alternative arrangements such as booking a confirmed ticket on another train, opting for a different class, or exploring other modes of transportation.\n\n### **Final Tips**\n\n- **Stay Informed:** Regularly monitor your ticket status through the railway's official website, app, or by contacting customer service.\n- **Early Booking:** To minimize the chances of ending up with a waitlisted ticket, try to book your tickets well in advance, especially during peak travel seasons.\n- **Travel Flexibility:** If possible, keep your travel dates and times flexible to increase the likelihood of securing a confirmed seat.\n\nFor the most accurate and personalized assistance, consider contacting the railway's customer support or visiting the PRS counter where you purchased your ticket.",
